text: Absolutely right. And it does influence how we build models. So as you say, corporate credit has natural breadth. We have literally thousands of issuers and more thousands of bonds, but each of them is lower liquidity. So the key there is to harness breadth as far as possible by building a very diversified portfolio, but also to be aware of the liquidity or potential illiquidity of those positions. Can you trade into the positions and what's the consequence of building a big position in terms of illiquidity? So the focus there is very much on liquidity modeling, optimization, transaction cost modeling, and exploiting the natural breadth. Rates is a different area. There is more natural liquidity in government bonds, in interest rate swaps, in futures, et cetera, but there's much less natural breadth. Why is that? If you're looking in developed market space, say interest rate swaps, you've probably got maximum about 15 different issuers, a few more if you go to EM space, but then... You start going down the liquidity spectrum. So there's much less issuer breadth. So what do we do given that we want breadth? It's the single most important thing in the whole of investing to have breadth and diversification. We create it by building trade exposures, which are uncorrelated, or at least not fully correlated to each other. So in rates, for example, we trade the level of the yield curve, but actually we put much more risk into trading slope curve. We've recently built a volatility strategy, and then... We've built a volatility strategy, and then we've built a then there are plenty of other things that you can do to create uncorrelated trades. Break-even inflation is one of them, basis, et cetera. So the breadth that we create there is by building models across different types of rates exposure. And the result of that is a process where you can create diversification. I think it's worth mentioning at this point, that is a key advantage of systematic investing where you can build a backtest is you can show what these correlations actually are. So we wouldn't be able to create as much breadth in rate space without the ability to build models and to backtest them. That said, probably even with all that, the breadth is naturally less than corporate credit. And hence, you would expect a lower quality of returns in terms of information ratio or IC than in corporate credit space, but there's less risk and less need to model a liquidity. So that's probably where the relative focuses are, liquidity and optimization in credit and the breadth question on the rate side. Thank you.
